1. b3 e5 2. Bb2 Nc6 3. e3 d5 4. Bb5 Bd6 5. f4 {. When I open a game with 1 b3!,
this is my dream line. In this chapter Black declares open contempt for our
opening and promptly accepts our challenge by taking control over the centre
with ...e7-e5 and ...d7-d5. But as you can see from the diagram, it's hard to
decide whether Black's centre represents a blessing or a curse, since e5 is
under heavy assault. To my mind Black's meagre gains feel disproportionate to
the vast expenditure of energy invested in defending the optimistic enterprise.
We twist, knead and pound the beleaguered e5-property, which Black jealously
protects, to the shape of our will: -- 1. Black's pinned knight isn't much of
a defender of e5 and we may also inflict damage to his structure by chopping
the knight at a later date. -- 2. Black can't play ...e5xf4?? since g7 hangs,
so he suffers a second pin. -- 3. Nf3 is coming, and Black must either play ...Bg4 and ...Bxf3 - which negates his bishop pair advantage (remember, we will
trade on c6), leaving him with the worse structure - or will be forced to
contort further and pour more resources down the aperture of his optimistic
plan with a future ...Qe7 and ...f7-f6. -- 4. We may further enhance our
structure by playing a future f4xe5, which swaps a wing pawn for Black's
central pawn, and also opens the f-file for our rook. --- Saying all this,
let's keep our guard up, since Black's inherent freedom and coming piece
activity can easily transform into dangerous attacks, especially if we don't
know our lines cold. I mentioned in the introduction to the book that 1 b3 is
basically an intuitive opening, without much need for memorization. Well, in
this chapter, forget I said that! The arising positions in this chapter are
sharp, forcing lines, susceptible to computer preparation. So let's do our
homework in this chapter and rewards will follow. Wing it, and we risk
disaster.} *

