1. b3 e5 2. Bb2 Nc6 3. e3 Nf6 4. Bb5 Bd6 5. Na3 {. This odd, fragmentary line,
with its manifold, intricate byways, has the power to befuddle both Black and
White. The diagrammed position above looks like a game between inebriated
beginners at a bar - the loser to pay for the next round of drinks - and has
to be one of the most outlandish tabiya positions in memory. Matters progress
in ever more bugged out fashion from here on, where White's antisocial
a3-knight often heads for c2 or even back to b1. Meanwhile Black, striving not
to be outdone in this contest of the unnatural, plugs up queenside development
by posting his bishop on what looks like its worst possible outpost on d6. ---
Black's intent, as explained in more detail in the first game of the chapter,
is to engineer a future ...d7-d5, without wasting an earlier tempo on ...d7-d6.
The even stranger part is that the state of current theory suggests this line
may be Black's optimum choice versus our Nimzo-Larsen, and is the current
darling of many of the world's top GMs, suggesting that we had better give
this line respect. --- After I sent Everyman this chapter, editor GM John Emms
described the variation perfectly in his email response: "I don't think I'll
use this line to teach kids about opening play!"} *

