1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Bb5 {. The actors are different and a few
props have been altered, but the play remains the same as in normal
Nimzo-Indians. In this chapter we arrive in reversed Nimzos a move up, albeit
with White committed to a queenside fianchetto, since we made that decision on
our very first move. Here we face the most classical of opponents, unafraid to
play the opening a full move down. The fight tends to revolve around control
over e5. We play an eventual Bxc6 and then target the e5-square, occupying it
with Ne5 and f2-f4. From there, our struggles are inscribed upon the pages of
the kingside, the arena in which we struggle for a direct attack on the enemy
king. Meanwhile, Black nurses ambitions on the queenside and hopes for a happy
future with his newly acquired bishop pair. Sometimes we are lucky enough to
inflict damage on Black's structure when he responds to Bxc6 with ...b7xc6. In
this case we are not obliged to attack and, instead, may play purely on his
damaged structure.} *

