1. b3 Nf6 2. Bb2 g6 3. Bxf6 exf6 {. Black, believing he or she is about to
enter some form of King's Indian or Grünfeld, replies to our Nimzo-Larsen with
1...Nf6 and 2...g6. We, in turn, respond by chopping the f6-knight, in strange,
inverted Trompowsky fashion. Our plan: control over d5, starting with c2-c4,
Nc3, g2-g3 and Bg2. In this case, we get a better version than in a normal
Trompowsky. Why? Because after 1 d4 Nf6 2 Bg5 g6 3 Bxf6 exf6, Black's
counterplay fulcrum tends to revolve around the e4-square. He usually
continues with ...f6-f5, ...Bg7, ...0-0, ...Re8, ...d7-d6 and ...Nd7-f6. But
note that in our Nimzo-Larsen version, our d-pawn has been held back, so we
can play d2-d3, denying Black use of the all-important e4-square. This fine
point allows White to extract a strategic edge against Black's move order, and
we often see the door to Black's standard kingside counterplay slamming shut
with the sound of finality.} *

